        },
        {
          "id": 68459,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">20 ppm</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 10-year-old boy from a village in Rajasthan, India, is evaluated after presenting with mottled and rough ridges on his teeth. Similar dental conditions, as well as deformities of the long bones, have been observed in other villagers. Upon investigation, the local water supply is found to have elevated levels of fluoride. With a diagnosis of dental fluorosis made, what concentration of fluoride in the water is likely to cause these findings?<strong> </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/11/screenshot-2024-04-11-103112.png\" style=\"height:302px; width:300px\" /></strong></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4189527",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30590,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C) 5 ppm</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Fluoride </strong>prevents <strong>caries</strong>, as topical application of <strong>fluoride </strong>will result in a<strong> fluorapatite layer on the enamel, </strong>which <strong>protects enamel </strong>from the<strong> decay by acid.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The<strong> safe limit</strong> of fluorine is about <strong>1 ppm</strong> in water.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Fluoride level &gt;&gt;2 ppm</strong> causes<strong> chronic intestinal upset, gastroenteritis, loss of appetite and loss of weight. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Level &gt;&gt;5 ppm</strong> causes <strong>mottling of enamel, stratification and discoloration of teeth.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A <strong>level &gt;&gt;&gt;20 ppm</strong> is <strong>toxic</strong> &rarr; causes alternate areas of <strong>osteoporosis and osteosclerosis</strong> with brittle bones known as <strong>fluorosis.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A. 1 ppm:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> While <strong>1 ppm</strong> is generally the <strong>optimal </strong>level for <strong>fluoride</strong> in drinking water to <strong>prevent tooth decay, </strong>it does <strong>not</strong> typically cause<strong> fluorosis,</strong> which occurs from <strong>higher</strong> levels of <strong>fluoride exposure.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B. 2 ppm:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This <strong>level of fluoride</strong> can begin to cause <strong>dental fluorosis,</strong> especially in <strong>children </strong>who are exposed over <strong>long periods,</strong> but the <strong>skeletal manifestations</strong> such as<strong> deformity of long bones </strong>are <strong>less </strong>common at this concentration.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D. 20 ppm:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> At this concentration, <strong>fluoride</strong> would likely cause <strong>severe skeletal fluorosis</strong> in addition to <strong>dental fluorosis.</strong> The manifestations in the <strong>village</strong> suggest a <strong>high level of fluoride </strong>but do <strong>not</strong> necessarily indicate a level as<strong> high as 20 ppm</strong>, which would be expected to cause <strong>widespread,</strong> severe <strong>skeletal problems.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Dental fluorosis </strong>is a <strong>chronic</strong> condition caused by <strong>excessive intake of fluorine</strong> compounds, leading to <strong>mottling of teeth </strong>and, in severe cases, <strong>skeletal fluorosis,</strong> which can include <strong>deformity of long bones.</strong> <strong>Fluoride levels</strong> in drinking water exceeding<strong> 1.5 ppm </strong>(parts per million) can cause <strong>dental fluorosis,</strong> but the severe symptoms described, including <strong>deformity of long bones</strong>, are often observed at <strong>higher concentrations</strong>, typically around <strong>5 ppm or more.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Vasudevan 9/e: p522.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
