      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Which mineral is known to have a sparing action on vitamin E, thereby enhancing its antioxidant effects in the body?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8566596",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30589,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans.&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">B) Selenium</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Selenium </strong>is known to have a <strong>sparing action </strong>on <strong>vitamin E</strong>. Both <strong>selenium and vitamin E </strong>function as <strong>antioxidants </strong>in the body, <strong>protecting cell membranes </strong>from<strong> oxidative damage</strong>. Selenium is a <strong>component </strong>of the enzyme <strong>glutathione peroxidase</strong>, which works in concert with <strong>vitamin E to prevent oxidative stress in cells</strong>. This <strong>synergistic action means </strong>that <strong>adequate selenium levels </strong>can help to <strong>reduce </strong>the <strong>requirement for vitamin E</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A. Chromium:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Incorrect </strong>because <strong>chromium </strong>is primarily involved in <strong>glucose metabolism </strong>and <strong>insulin </strong>function, <strong>not </strong>in sparing vitamin E. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C. Iron:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Incorrect </strong>because iron, while <strong>essential </strong>for many <strong>biological processes</strong>, can actually <strong>promote oxidative stress </strong>in <strong>excessive amounts </strong>and does <strong>not </strong>have a sparing action on vitamin E. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D. Magnesium:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Incorrect </strong>because <strong>magnesium&#39;s </strong>primary roles include <strong>enzyme function</strong>, <strong>energy production</strong>, and <strong>muscle contraction</strong>, and it is <strong>not </strong>directly involved in<strong> sparing</strong> <strong>vitamin E</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Selenium&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">acts as a nonspecific <strong>intracellular antioxidant. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">This action of<strong> Se </strong>is<strong> complementary </strong>to <strong>vitamin E</strong>. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Availability of <strong>vitamin E reduces </strong>the <strong>selenium requirement</strong> and in<strong> Se deficiency,</strong> tissue <strong>vitamin E </strong>content is<strong> depleted.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Vasudevan 9/e: 523.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
